    {
      "id": "RPi-WW_HF9sId9ndsoPsp",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1257.9223800078712,
      "y": 247.10181124664945,
      "width": 1806.825069375421,
      "height": 620.7219787686505,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [
        "SwfGgqDA8s2v6k3oYsPX9"
      ],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2G",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 459099985,
      "version": 3377,
      "versionNonce": 1927300735,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1772583981878,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": " API Server — Exposes endpoints for creating, deleting, and retrieving jobs (CRD operations). On write, the API Server inserts a row into the job-schedules table, calculates the next  \n  execution time bucket, and inserts a corresponding row into task-schedules.\n                                                                                                                                                                                          \n  NoSQL Database — A NoSQL database is a better fit than relational here. There are no requirements for table relationships, complex joins, or ACID transactions. The scheduler needs\nto handle 500 jobs per second, and NoSQL databases scale horizontally, making them well suited for high write throughput.\n\n  Message Queue (SQS) — Provides built-in retry with exponential backoff for failed jobs, message delay for scheduling future execution, and message deduplication to prevent duplicate\nprocessing.\n\n  Master Server — Runs as multiple instances, each with a background task that executes every minute. It queries task-schedules for rows where the next execution time bucket is\nwithin the current minute and status is NOT_STARTED, then enqueues a message per task into SQS. Since multiple master instances may read the same rows, SQS message\ndeduplication prevents duplicate processing. After enqueuing, the master updates the task status to SCHEDULED.\n\n  Worker Servers — Multiple instances consume messages from SQS and execute the job via API call. On success: the task-schedules table is updated with the next execution time, the\nhistory table is updated with a success status, and the message is deleted from the queue. On failure: the message remains on the queue with a configured retry delay, and the history\ntable is updated with the error and attempt count.\n\n  ---\n  Alternative: Optimistic Locking\n\n  Instead of relying on SQS deduplication, an optimistic lock via versioning can prevent duplicate processing. Each master instance reads a task row and performs a conditional write —\n  updating the status only if the version field is 0. This ensures only one instance claims each task. However, there is a risk: a master could claim a task (update the version) but\n  crash before enqueuing the message to SQS. To handle this, a lightweight recovery task periodically resets the version back to 0 for any row that has been in SCHEDULED status\nlonger than a configured timeout window.\n ",
      "fontSize": 19.863103320596814,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": " API Server — Exposes endpoints for creating, deleting, and retrieving jobs (CRD operations). On write, the API Server inserts a row into the job-schedules table, calculates the next   \n  execution time bucket, and inserts a corresponding row into task-schedules.\n                                                                                                                                                                                          \n  NoSQL Database — A NoSQL database is a better fit than relational here. There are no requirements for table relationships, complex joins, or ACID transactions. The scheduler needs to handle 500 jobs per second, and NoSQL databases scale horizontally, making them well suited for high write throughput.\n\n  Message Queue (SQS) — Provides built-in retry with exponential backoff for failed jobs, message delay for scheduling future execution, and message deduplication to prevent duplicate processing.\n\n  Master Server — Runs as multiple instances, each with a background task that executes every minute. It queries task-schedules for rows where the next execution time bucket is within the current minute and status is NOT_STARTED, then enqueues a message per task into SQS. Since multiple master instances may read the same rows, SQS message deduplication prevents duplicate processing. After enqueuing, the master updates the task status to SCHEDULED.\n\n  Worker Servers — Multiple instances consume messages from SQS and execute the job via API call. On success: the task-schedules table is updated with the next execution time, the history table is updated with a success status, and the message is deleted from the queue. On failure: the message remains on the queue with a configured retry delay, and the history table is updated with the error and attempt count.\n\n  ---\n  Alternative: Optimistic Locking\n\n  Instead of relying on SQS deduplication, an optimistic lock via versioning can prevent duplicate processing. Each master instance reads a task row and performs a conditional write —\n  updating the status only if the version field is 0. This ensures only one instance claims each task. However, there is a risk: a master could claim a task (update the version) but\n  crash before enqueuing the message to SQS. To handle this, a lightweight recovery task periodically resets the version back to 0 for any row that has been in SCHEDULED status longer than a configured timeout window.\n ",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    }
